      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the memory usage issue is indeed a common one in the realm of transaction processing. It seems like your `processTransactions` function is creating a new `Transaction` object for each transaction in the batch. This is a classic case of the \"new\" operator being used in a loop, which can lead to a gradual increase in memory usage, as each `Transaction` object is not being deleted after processing.\n\nTo address this, you should consider moving the creation of the `Transaction` objects outside of the loop. This way, you're creating all the objects at once and then processing them in a single pass. Here's how you could refactor your code:\n\n```cpp\nvoid processTransactions(Transaction* txs, int count) {\n    Transaction* transactions = new Transaction[count];\n    for (int i = 0; i < count; ++i) {\n        transactions[i] = new Transaction(txs[i]);\n        // ... some logic to process the transaction ...\n        if (transactions[i]->isProcessed()) {\n            updateLedger(transactions[i]);\n        }\n    }\n    // Don't forget to delete the transactions array to free up memory\n    delete[] transactions;\n}\n```\n\nBy doing this, you're ensuring that the memory is allocated only once",
      "source": "target",
