      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. My previous explanation was indeed incorrect. The memory leak persists because we are still allocating memory for each `Transaction` object within the loop. To truly fix the memory leak, we should remove the `new Transaction(txs[i])` call from inside the loop and instead create all the `Transaction` objects before entering the loop. Here's the corrected version of the code:\n\n```cpp\nvoid processTransactions(Transaction* txs, int count) {\n    Transaction* transactions = new Transaction[count];\n    for (int i = 0; i < count; ++i) {\n        transactions[i] = new Transaction(txs[i]);\n        // ... some logic to process the transaction ...\n        if (transactions[i]->isProcessed()) {\n            updateLedger(transactions[i]);\n        }\n    }\n    // Don't forget to delete the transactions array to free up memory\n    delete[] transactions;\n}\n```\n\nNow, the `Transaction` objects are created once before the loop, and we only need to delete the array of `Transaction` objects once after the loop to prevent memory leaks. This way, we're not repeatedly allocating memory for each transaction within the loop, which should resolve the memory usage issue.",
